Here, you are relying on the 1-800-xxx-xxx being read from configuration.

A unit test should not need to do this. You should only care that it calls ConfigManager.getString() and instruct it on what to return.
You need to use JMockit for this as its a static method.

Personally I&#39;d make the LEAVE_REQUEST_WRAP_UP_MESSAGE public and to a proper String equals check here, rather than just checking the string contains the phone number.

e.g.

new Expectations(ConfigManager.class) {{
ConfigManager.getString(LEAVE_REQUEST_WRAP_UP_APPLICATION_CATEGORY, CONTACT_NUMBER_PROPERTY);
result = contactNumber ;
}};

final String expectedMessage = MessageFormat.format(SUMMARY_MESSAGE, contactNumber);

assertThat(widget.getLeaveRequestSummaryMessage(), is(expectedMessage));

